# Python Conventions

## StrEnum for all string identifiers

Use `StrEnum` classes (defined in `schema.py`) for node types, edge types, and field/property names. Never use raw string literals for these values.

```python
# Bad
G.add_node(nid, type="post", text="hello")

# Good
from schema import NodeType, Field
G.add_node(nid, **{Field.TYPE: NodeType.POST, Field.TEXT: "hello"})
```

## Shared config file at project root

All configurable constants (paths, URLs, model names, thresholds) live in `config.py` at the project root. Import from there; do not hardcode values in individual modules.

```python
# Bad
LLM_BASE_URL = "http://localhost:8080/v1"

# Good
from config import LLM_BASE_URL
```

## Imports always at the top of the file

All imports go at module level. Never use inline imports inside functions or methods.

## No sys.path hacking

Do not use `sys.path.insert` or `sys.path.append` to fix import resolution. The project uses `pythonpath` in `pyproject.toml` (`[tool.pytest.ini_options]`) to make the root and component directories importable. Run scripts from the project root.

## No underscore-prefixed class names

Never name a class with a leading underscore. Use a clear, descriptive name instead. If the class is internal to a module, that's already communicated by not exporting it.

## No unnecessary try/except

Avoid wrapping code in try/except blocks unless there is a specific, justified reason to catch and handle that exception.
